Use CART and GAMs to predict the out of state tuition

This question uses the College data set for the ISLR package and is modified from Question 10 (a) from Chapter 7.

1 Create training/test data.

Read in the data and view the column names. Split the data into a 65% training set and a test set. Use a seed of 333.

set.seed(157)

# Read in the College dataset 
df_col <- College

# Split the data into Training and Testing (65% and 35%, respectively)
col_split <- initial_split(df_col, prop = .60) 
col_train <- rsample::training(col_split) 
col_test <- rsample::testing(col_split)

# View Column names
names(df_col)

Use a recipe to create datasets that have their predictor variables converted so nominal variables become dummys and all predictors are normalized. Use the recipe on the data so you end up with a full/original normalized dataset, a training normalized dataset, and a testing normalized dataset.

# Create a recipe to preprocess the data
col_recipe <- recipe(Outstate ~ ., data = df_col) %>% 
  step_dummy(all_nominal(), one_hot = TRUE) %>%
  step_normalize(all_numeric_predictors()) %>%
  prep()

# Apply the recipe to the training and testing sets
col_train_baked <- bake(col_recipe, new_data = col_train)
col_test_baked <- bake(col_recipe, new_data = col_test)
col_full_baked <- bake(col_recipe, new_data = df_col)

3 GAM models

3a. Fit a full GAM on the training data

Fit a GAM using out-of-state tuition as the response and the variables/features selected in the previous step (from the Regression Tree) as the predictors using the normalized training data.

For the full GAM model, use cubic smoothers for all the predictors except Private (which is qualitative). We do want to use the Private variable, but note it now has a new name in the normalized dataset.

View the summary of the results.

#Define the model specification
gam_spec <- gen_additive_mod() %>%
              set_engine("mgcv", importance = "impurity") %>%
              set_mode("regression")
#Fit the model
gam_col_fit <- gam_spec %>%
  fit(Outstate ~ s(Expend, bs = "cr") + s(S.F.Ratio, bs = "cr") + 
        s(PhD, bs = "cr") + s(Terminal, bs = "cr") + s(Top10perc, bs = "cr") +
        s(Top25perc, bs = "cr") + s(F.Undergrad, bs = "cr") + 
        s(Enroll, bs = "cr") + s(Accept, bs = "cr") + s(P.Undergrad, bs = "cr")+
        Private_Yes + Private_No,
      data = col_train_baked)

How do the metrics metrics compare to the Regression Tree? The Pruned GAMs Model performed slightly better than the regression tree because it has a slightly higher R-squared value. It also has both a lower Mean Absolute Error and Root Mean Square Error which signifies that the Pruned GAMs model has a lower average difference between its predicted values and the actual values, rather than the Regression Tree which has more error.

Read in the data. Perform the following tasks in this order.

  • Remove the variables mas_vnr_area, overall_cond, sale_price, bldg_type, land_contour, ms_zoning, land_slope, sale_condition, lot_config, central_air
  • We want to predict a categorical version of overall quality so change overall_qual to be âHighâ if the quality is greater than or equal to 7. Make it âLowâ otherwise. Specify the factor levels so that the âmost important eventâ is âHighâ (should be first in levels)
  • Combine categories in house_style that have too few categories with: mutate(house_style = if_else(house_style %in% c('1.5Unf', '2.5Fin', '2.5Unf', 'SFoyer', 'SLvl'), 'Other', house_style ))

Identify columns where you can recode them to have fewer categories. For example, you can add âotherâ to combine categories that are small. Update the character variables so that the smallest category has at least 50 values. You can use code similar to our recoding of house_style above.

df_house <- df_house %>% 
  mutate(mas_vnr_type = if_else(mas_vnr_type %in% c('BrkCmn','Stone'), 'Other',
                               mas_vnr_type )) %>% 
  mutate(exter_qual = if_else(exter_qual %in% c('Fa', 'Ex'), 'Other',
                               exter_qual )) %>% 
  mutate(foundation = if_else(foundation %in% c('Slab', 'Stone','BrkTil'), 'Other',
                               foundation )) %>% 
  mutate(fireplace_qu = if_else(fireplace_qu %in% c('Ex', 'Fa', 'Po'), 'Other',
                               fireplace_qu )) %>% 
  mutate(garage_type = if_else(garage_type %in% c('2Types', 'Basment',
                                                  'CarPort','BuiltIn'),'Other',
                               garage_type ))

6b. Define the Recipe for Data Preparation and Bake

Create a recipe using using step_normalize() for all the numeric predictors and the step_dummy() for all the nominal predictor variables. Since we are using SVC, we also need to check for zero variance. Add step_zv to the recipe that you used for HW2. You will also use prep() so that you can also run/bake this recipe.

Use the recipe to create a normalized dataset for your analysis

house_recipe <- recipe(overall_qual ~ ., data = df_house) %>% 
  step_dummy(all_nominal(), one_hot = TRUE) %>%
  step_normalize(all_numeric_predictors()) %>%
  prep()

6c. Split the data into a 70% training set and a test set.

Use a seed (2934) so that you can replicate your own results. Split the normalized data into training and test datasets. Make sure to stratify on overall_qual.

set.seed(2934)

house_split <- initial_split(df_house, prop = .70, strata = overall_qual) 
house_train <- rsample::training(house_split) 
house_test <- rsample::testing(house_split)

house_train_baked <- bake(house_recipe, new_data = house_train)
house_test_baked <- bake(house_recipe, new_data = house_test)
house_full_baked <- bake(house_recipe, new_data = df_house)

6d. Create the metrics set

For our analyses, we want to have the accuracy, sensitivity, and specificity for these models. So create a metrics_set that you can reuse for all our models. (When you store the results later, you will also calculate the error rate manually from the accuracy.)

my_metrics <- metric_set(yardstick::accuracy, 
                         yardstick::sensitivity, 
                         yardstick::specificity)

ROC_threshold <- function(pred_data,truth,probs) {
 
  roc_curve_tbl <- pred_data %>% 
                    roc_curve(truth = {{truth}}, {{probs}}) 
  auc = pred_data %>%
              roc_auc(truth = {{truth}}, {{probs}}) %>%
              pull(.estimate)
  best_row = which.max(roc_curve_tbl$specificity + roc_curve_tbl$sensitivity)
  print(paste("Best Cutoff:", round(roc_curve_tbl[best_row,'.threshold'],4),
              "Sensitivity:", round(roc_curve_tbl[best_row,'sensitivity'],4),
              "Specificity:", round(roc_curve_tbl[best_row,'specificity'],4),
              "AUC for Model:", round(auc,4)))
}
